{{Short description|Kofun period Kofun cluster in Matsue, Shimane, Japan}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Kinzaki Kofun cluster | native_name =金崎古墳群 | native_name_lang = | image = Kinzakikofungun 01.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Kinzaki No.1 | map_type = Japan Shimane Prefecture#Japan | map_alt = location in Japan | relief = 1 | map_caption = Kinzaki Kofun cluster | map_size = 270px | altitude_m = | altitude_ref = | coordinates = {{coord|35|29|21.5|N|133|04|12.7|E|display=inline, title}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Matsue, Shimane]], [[Japan]] | region = [[San'in region]] | type = [[Kofun]] | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = | built =5th century AD | abandoned = | epochs = [[Kofun period]] | cultures = | discovered = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = Yes | Historic Site = | website = | architectural_styles = | architectural_details = | notes = {{box|background=white|align=center|wide=yes|border size=3px|border color=brown|text align=center|[[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]]}} {{maplink2|type=point|frame=yes|plain=yes|zoom=12|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|coord={{coord|35|29|21.5|N|133|04|12.7|E|}}}}}}
The {{nihongo|'''Kinzaki Kofun cluster'''|金崎古墳群| Kinzaki Kofun-gun}} is a group of [[Kofun period]] [[kofun|Kofun]]s located in Nishikawatsu neighborhood of the city of [[Matsue, Shimane|Matsue]], [[Shimane Prefecture]], in the [[San'in region]] of [[Japan]]. The tumuli were collectively designated a National Historic Site in 1957.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/139367|title=金崎古墳群|trans-title= Kinzaki Kofun-gun|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 31, 2022}}</ref>
==Overview== The Kinzaki Kofun cluster is located behind [[Shimane University]], on a small hill overlooking the lowlands downstream of the Asakumi River to the south. It consists of two "two conjoined rectangles" type ({{nihongo|''{{ill|zenpō-kōhō-fun|lt=zenpō-kōhō-fun|ja|前方後方墳|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=}}''|前方後方墳|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun}}), and three {{ill|Square Kofun|lt=square-type|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|qq=}} ({{nihongo|''hōfun''|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}) ''kofun''. There were originally 11 Kofuns, but six were destroyed due to the construction of a nearby housing complex in 1963. [[Archaeological excavation]] of Kofun No. 1 in 1947 determined that the [[burial chamber]] was a pit-style stone chamber made of split stones. A wide variety of [[grave goods]] were excavated, including a [[bronze mirror]] with a flower pattern, several ''[[magatama]]'' and several other types of beads, an iron blade, and [[Sue pottery]] pottery. The Sue pottery belongs to the oldest style in the San'in region, and there are few unusual examples such as vessel stands, vessels with bells, and vessels with legs.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The site is approximately 3.4 kilometers, or a 40-minute walk, north of [[Matsue Station]] on the [[JR West]] [[San'in Main Line]].
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;background:#ffffff;white-space:nowrap;font-size:85%" |+ Kinzaki Kofun cluster !name !type !Size |- | Kinzaki No.1||''zenpō-kōhō-fun''||total length 32 meters: anterior: 12 x 14 x 1 meters; posterior 20 x 23.5 x 3 meters |- | Kinzaki No. 2|| ''hōfun'' || 10 x 10 x 1 meters |- | Kinzaki No. 3|| ''hōfun'' || 20 x 20 x 2 meters |- | Kinzaki No. 4|| ''hōfun'' || 26.5 x 17 x 3 meters |- | Kinzaki No.5||''zenpō-kōhō-fun''||total length 22 meters: anterior: 5 x 7.5 x 1 meters; posterior 17 x 20 x 2.5 meters |}
